	<div class="container" id="research-template">
		<div class="row">
			<div class="col-md-2">
				<img class="logo img-responsive" src="${request.static_url('dbas:static/images/logo.png')}" alt="dbas logo">
			</div>
			<div class="col-md-10">
				<div class="content">
					<h2><span class="font-semi-bold">Research</span> <span class="smaller">of D-BAS</span></h2>
					<ul class="lead list">
						<li>
							<span class="font-normal">Our data structure:</span>
							<br>We are using a argumentation map as data structure, whereby our map is a four-tuple &lt;P,A,R,v&gt; with:
							<ul class="lead list">
								<li>P is the set of positions</li>
								<li>A is the set of arguments</li>
								<li>R is the set of relations:</li>
									<ul>
										<li>attacking/supporting in A</li>
										<li>attacking/supporting in P</li>
										<li>attacking/supporting in A united P</li>
									</ul>
								<li>v is the function for evaluating A and P</li>
							</ul>
							We are also supposing that attack- and support-relations must have different elements out of A and R. 
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="lead">In addition, we have studied several tools:</p>
					<ul class="lead list">
						<li>
							<span class="font-normal">Forum:</span>
							<br>Forum-based approaches are well known to all kind of users, but are only scale with the number of users, not with the number of arguments. Therefore messages can be highly redundant. Additionally the messages are not connected logically to each other.
						</li>
						<li>
							<span class="font-normal">Pro-Contra Lists:</span>
							<br>These lists are more arranged than the forum-based approaches, but even there are no connections between the arguments. Therefore these approaches are just lists and not more.
						</li>
						<li>
							<span class="font-normal">Argumentation-based Approaches:</span>
							<br>This concept seems to be perfect, because posts are connected logically to each other and redundancy can be avoided. Unfortunately these tools are for experts only and not for amateurs.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<span class="font-normal">For these reason the novel approach of a dialogue-based argumendation system was developed.</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
